It is an honor to congratulate, Miss Rachel Gomez, runner up for Region 19‚Äôs Teacher of the Year!

Miss Gomez was named Sierra Blanca School's Elementary Teacher of Year in May and went on to compete for the Region‚Äôs title. She was one of twelve teachers who participated in a series of interviews and was selected as runner up for the region.

Miss Gomez has been teaching third, fourth and fifth grade English Language Arts and Social Studies at Sierra Blanca School since 2017.
Creating a fun and interactive learning environment, Miss Gomez inspires her students while lovingly and steadfastly holding them to the highest expectations. Her hard work, dedication and love for teaching is an inspiration to her students and coworkers alike.

Congratulations to Miss Gomez!
Thank you for your hard work and dedication to Sierra Blanca School and our community!

post_text:
Your household may be eligible to receive Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) benefits to buy food.

P-EBT is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
Congratulations to Sierra Blanca School‚Äôs Secondary Teacher of the Year:
Mr. Francisco Rodriguez!

When visiting the campus, one might wonder about the amount of blue painter‚Äôs tape on the floor marking angles and quadrants. Sometimes, it is necessary to be on the lookout for falling objects like padded eggs or paper rockets. These are the kinds of activities that make learning and teaching fun and are just a couple of ways that Mr. Francisco Rodriguez connects learning and life for his students!

Mr. Francisco Rodriguez promotes excellence for the students of Sierra Blanca School! He is in his second year of teaching financial literacy and high school math.
Before becoming a teacher, Mr. Rodriguez was an accountant. But he saw and opportunity to help the students of Sierra Blanca School learn these important skills and meet their goals ‚Äì and he‚Äôs been doing just that every day!

Thank you to Mr. Francisco Rodriguez for his continuous commitment to our students and congratulations on this much-deserved recognition!

Most of you probably have already heard the Governor‚Äôs directive about schools continuing instruction remotely for the remainder of the school year. While it‚Äôs not what we have been hoping for, the health and safety of our students, staff and community will always be our number one priority. We will continue delivering meals and lessons as we have been.
We are looking forward to the day that we can hug and high five each and every one of you inside our school building! You have handled this ever-changing and uncertain time we‚Äôre in with such poise. We are SO proud of each of you and your Vaquero strength and spirit! Keep up the great work!

Thanks to all the parents who have submitted concerns and questions about the work that is going home this week, and a BIG thank you for being patient with us as we learn as we go.

The work that is being sent home Monday and Tuesday is designed to be a review of what students have already been taught, in order to prepare them for the tests that are coming on Wednesday and Thursday. You should not have to teach your child anything. They need to work on the assignment (and give a very diligent, honest try at it). If your child does not understand the work, please do not hesitate to contact your child‚Äôs teacher right away. He/She will gladly give your child any additional instruction they need. On Wednesday and Thursday most students will have a test to complete for some classes.

Again thank you for your feedback and if you have suggestions we are happy to consider any idea!

post_text: Sierra Blanca ISD is currently considering the best options available to our school in light of the Corona virus or COVID 19 that, first and foremost, prudently protects the health of students, staff and the community, but also fulfills our obligation to education. Five area superintendents collaborated on a presentation about how Lone Star Governance has helped school districts monitor and promote academic success for all students.

Ebby Loeffler, Superintendent of Sierra Blanca School, Dr. Oscar Tronozco of Anthony ISD, Dr. Veronica Vijil from Fabens ISD, Rosy Vega-Barrio of Tornillo ISD, Dr. Jeannie Meza-Chavez and Monica Jaloma with Region 19 Education Service Center presented at the 50th Annual Mexican America School Board Association Conference in San Antonio over the weekend.

One of the primary goals of Mexican American School Board Associate is to ensure that all students have an opportunity to succeed at a high level and to close barriers that lead to achievement gaps among demographic subgroups. Region 19 schools have a history of success in student achievement and closing gaps.

Sierra Blanca Board of Trustees also joined the conference to support Region 19 and these superintendents and to continue their own learning in order to continue the growth and success of Sierra Blanca School.

post_text:
We kicked off the spring semester today with a back to school assembly! This new year is all about teamwork, character building and leadership for the students and teachers at Sierra Blanca School.

Students were divided into 10 multi-grade-level teams and will spend the semester earning...and losing points for their team. Students earn points for high marks on assessments, academic growth and outstanding character. They can also earn points for turning in reading logs and/or taking Accelerated Reader tests. Points are taken away for unexcused absence, tardies or discipline referrals.
Students met in the gym this morning for a fast paced and fun team building tournament, where Team Better Than Anyone Else took the top prize!
What a great day to be a Vaquero and start of a great semester!

post_text: Freshmen and Sophomore students who are considering careers in medicine were invited by Texas Tech Health Science Center and Desert Mountain Area Health Education Center to an exploration opportunity at Van Horn High School. Students learned about the many careers in medicine and medical support. They had opportunities to learn how to save choking babies, intubate patients, and suture wounds. They had opportunities to hear from three medical students about what they should be doing today to prepare for their dream jobs of tomorrow!

The Junior High volleyball season came to an end last week and what a great season it was! Our Junior High Lady Vaqueros finished with the record of 12 - 2. The girls worked hard all season and definitely put in the work!

I would like to thank the parents for coming out and supporting our Lady Vaqueros, for the early-morning practices, and sometimes late afternoon practices as well. Without your support our season could not have been as successful as it was!

Also, a big thank you to Ellayna Penalosa for volunteering her time to assist with the practices and her great encouragement throughout the games.

Once again thank you all for supporting our Lady Vaquero volleyball program and for Vaquero athletics!

Respectful & Thankful,
Coach Reyes

We would like to congratulate and extend well wishes to Principal Mrs. Bea Zavala!
Mrs. Zavala came to us out of retirement, and she is ready to return working on her retirement dreams! Her tremendous dedication to Sierra Blanca School has helped improve our school in so many ways and we are so grateful for her time, effort and talents!

We wish Mrs. Zavala well as she is looking forward to spending more time with life‚Äôs most precious gifts; like her husband Fred, their family and their farm.
Thankfully, Mrs. Zavala will still be available to support our students and staff as a consultant. She has agreed to help coordinate testing, bilingual student needs, UIL and any need that arises!

Once a Vaquero, Always a Vaquero!

post_text: Diego proudly represented the Vaqueros at the state golf meet in Austin on May 20-21. It was a great learning experience, as Diego had to face many new challenges on the Austin course that our desert golfer had not faced before. Diego said, ‚ÄúI learned so much that I can bring back to my team that I think will take us all to the state competition next year.‚Äù Diego had to develop new strategies on the spot to deal with the multitude of trees, high heat and humidity and rain. Coach Elo said, ‚ÄúDiego learned about strategy, about when to give up on a ball and take the stroke on a drop and how to shoot a 3-wood punch shot.‚Äù Even through the new experiences, Diego maintained great composure and ended the two day tournament in the top half of the field scoring a 192. Congratulations, Diego, on your fine performance!

GET TO KNOW THE VAQUEROS
Meet Mrs. Beatriz Zavala

Mrs. Beatriz Zavala is the principal at Sierra Blanca School.

She has been teaching, mentoring and leading area students for over 36 years. She began her career in education as a paraprofessional, then was a bilingual teacher and has been a principal for 30 years. Two years ago, Mrs. Zavala came to Sierra Blanca when she saw a wonderful opportunity to serve the students in our community. She is passionate about seeing students succeed! She encourages everyone at Sierra Blanca School to hold themselves to high standards, work hard and enjoy their success. She loves to see the teachers and students flourish in their work and is quick to honor them and celebrate their achievements. Her eye for design and attention to detail means that every event she has a hand in is beautifully decorated and enjoyed by all!

When she‚Äôs not at school, Mrs. Zavala and her husband Fred enjoy spending time together on their farm. She enjoys their cats, gardening and reading.

Congratulations to Joselyn on her selection to the Hugh O‚ÄôBrian Youth ‚Äì Far West Texas Leadership Seminar.

For more than 50 years, HOBY has been empowering high school sophomores to develop their leadership talents to become outstanding leaders of their community.

Joselyn will spend the next three days at the seminar, exploring and identifying her unique leadership skills. The seminar curriculum is based on the Social Change Model of Leadership and develops leadership from three perspectives: personal, group, and societal - through fun and interactive speakers, workshops, activities, and discussions.

GET TO KNOW THE VAQUEROS
Meet Ms. Guadalupe Pantoja

For the last five years, Ms. Guadalupe Pantoja has been supporting the students and staff at Sierra Blanca School. In her role with maintenance, it is her mission to ensure the school is a clean and safe environment for our students and staff. Always willing to help wherever she is needed, Lupe helps out in the cafeteria most days and works closely with the teachers and staff to make sure the campus is up to par.

Lupe came to Sierra Blanca from Delicias, Chihuahua when she was 16 years old with her sister. She is a supportive and proud Mom of three children, all of whom are Vaqueros.

When she is not at school, she enjoys taking care of her house and her granddaughter.

GET TO KNOW THE VAQUEROS
Meet Mrs. Guadalupe Acala

You won‚Äôt find a more dedicated and passionate teacher than Mrs. Guadalupe Acala! She has created a positive and exciting learning environment with endless possibilities for her class. Mrs. Acala says ‚Äúthere are no limits in education!‚Äù

Mrs. Acala‚Äôs classroom is structured and interactive. She encourages her students to interact with one another, utilize all of the technology and resources available, and ensures that they have every opportunity to learn. She believes that routine, a positive attitude, and a passion for learning are the keys to success.

Mrs. Acala has been teaching math and science to 4th and 5th grade Vaqueros for two years. With a degree in Education from UTEP, she began her career as a paraprofessional, then taught Head Start for twelve years. Mrs. Acala says she is thankful for the opportunity to join the Sierra Blanca School staff and has learned so much from her peers, mentors and students!

When she‚Äôs not at school, Mrs. Acala enjoys traveling with her husband and their children.

Graduation 2019 is less than two months away! We know we will have to say good-bye to an amazing senior class, but we are confident the legacy they leave behind will be filled by the students they have mentored over the years.
The Class of 2019 is an amazing class of leaders, and have played a crucial role in the vast improvement in our school performance over the last three years. They set high expectations for themselves and work hard to meet those expectations! They also step up to volunteer and help make our school a great place to learn and grow.
Recently Gio, Anthony, Noah, and Victor spent a day helping organize picture day, and made the process efficient and enjoyable for everyone! Thank you, gentlemen for your help and Class of 2019 for demonstrating the amazing heart of a Vaquero!

Always willing to help out and make sure things are running smoothly, Hector does the heavy lifting as the custodian, maintenance man, grounds keeper, and bus driver.

Hector came to Sierra Blanca in 1978 from Durango, Mexico. He graduated from Sierra Blanca School in 1986 and has been working at the school and ranching ever since. He and his wife of 35 years, Annie have 3 children and 7 grandchildren, who he enjoys spending time with and supporting them in all of their endeavors.

When he‚Äôs not working at school, Hector enjoys working on the ranch and occasionally playing a round of golf.

Victor may well be the hardest working high school student one may encounter. Victor is an honor student at Sierra Blanca School who is on-track to graduate with a distinguished level diploma. He has already amassed 18 college semester credit hours through the dual credit program.

Victor‚Äôs nomination for Student of the Week would be well deserved at any time; however, he is currently being nominated for his work in creating a YouTube Channel for Sierra Blanca School in which our daily announcements can be broadcast in classrooms through the use of Promethean boards. Victor has designed a newsroom set, and will be recording the announcements.

Additionally, Victor holds after-school jobs at the Exxon, Subway and at the Hudspeth County Appraisal District. He is a member of the local Border Patrol Explorers and has served as a leader in the organization. Victor is a talented musician as well, who hones his craft at every available opportunity.

Thank you, Victor, being one amazing Vaquero!

GET TO KNOW THE VAQUEROS
Meet Jenny Gomez

Mrs. Jenny Gomez teaches High School English, Journalism, Speech and Yearbook at Sierra Blanca School.

A 1997 UTEP graduate, Mrs. Gomez earned her degree in creative writing and a minor in secondary education. She began her teaching career at Socorro ISD in 1997, teaching Junior High English, Reading and Language Arts. She‚Äôs also taught elementary and Head Start.

Mrs. Gomez left the classroom for a few years to stay home raise her two wonderful children. She joined the Sierra Blanca School staff in 2014 in her current position.

Mrs. Gomez is constantly learning about her field of teaching through professional development and is passionate about building relationships with her students and colleagues. She genuinely cares for them and strives to help them meet their goals.

When she‚Äôs not at school, Mrs. Gomez enjoys reading and spending time with her husband Robert and their children, Liam and Amia.
